SIMPLE: winged
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Winged
<hw>Winged</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Furnished
with wings; transported by flying; having winglike expansions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Soaring with wings, or as if with wings; hence,
elevated; lofty; sublime.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How <qex>winged</qex> the sentiment that virtue is to be followed
for its own sake.</q> <rj><qau>J. S. Harford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Swift; rapid.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Bear this sealed brief
with <xex>winged</xex> haste to the lord marshal.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Wounded or hurt in the wing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Furnished with a leaflike
appendage, as the fruit of the elm and the ash, or the stem in certain
plants; alate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Represented with wings, or having
wings, of a different tincture from the body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Fanned with wings; swarming with birds.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>winged</xex> air darked with plumes.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winger</ent>⟦br⟧
